# Veil agent — parallel branches

Use **separate git branches** so multiple agents can execute different phase plans at the same time without one giant diff on `main`.

## Branch naming

| Pattern | Example |
|---------|---------|
| `engage/phase-<NN>-<slug>` | `engage/phase-24-ci-e2e` |
| `feat/<layer>-phase-<NN>-<slug>` | `feat/graph-phase-3-ingest-fix` |
| `platform/p0-<slug>` | `platform/p0-contract-consumer-tests` |

- `<NN>` = phase number from the master plan.
- `<slug>` = short kebab-case from the phase plan title (max ~4 words).

## Starting a phase (implementer agent)

1. Read the **master plan** and the **phase plan** for this stream only.
2. From up-to-date `main`:
   ```bash
   git fetch origin
   git checkout main && git pull origin main
   git checkout -b engage/phase-24-ci-e2e
   ```
3. In the **master plan** status table, record: phase id, branch name, status `in_progress`, optional stream label.
4. Implement → test → **commit on the branch** (one commit per slice within the phase is fine).
5. Push the branch: `git push -u origin HEAD`.
6. Open a PR to `main` (or hand off to the **critic agent**). Do not merge to `main` from an implementer session unless the user explicitly asked.

## Parallel streams

- **Independent phases** (different files, no shared `versions.env` edit): safe to run on separate branches concurrently.
- **Serial phases** (depends on prior phase merge): implementer waits until dependency is merged to `main`, then rebases:
  ```bash
  git fetch origin && git rebase origin/main
  ```
- **One branch = one phase** (or one explicit slice). Do not mix two phase plans on one branch.
- Conflicts on `versions.env`, shared catalog, or router: coordinate in the master plan — only one stream owns that file per wave, or merge sequentially.

## Merge discipline (avoid project drift)

**`main` is the integration branch.** Long-lived feature branches without merge cause painful conflicts and divergent behavior between agents.

| Rule | Action |
|------|--------|
| **Merge soon** | After critic APPROVE, merge to `main` within the same work wave (do not stack 3+ unmerged phase branches). |
| **One source of truth** | New work always starts from `git pull origin main`; never assume another branch is already merged. |
| **Before next parallel stream** | Merge completed phases to `main` first, then spawn the next implementer. |
| **Catch-up batch** | If user asks to merge all: order by dependency (platform P0 → engage 24 → 25 → …), resolve conflicts once, run full layer tests. |
| **Orchestrator default** | When user says «давай» / «продолжай», critic merges approved branches to `main` and pushes before starting the next phase. |

After each merge to `main`:

```bash
git checkout main && git pull origin main
make test-platform-p0   # if platform/pkg/bus touched
make test-engage        # if engage touched
make test-pipeline      # if pipeline touched
make test-graph         # if graph touched
make test-discovery     # if discovery touched
```

Then notify other streams: **rebase** open branches onto `origin/main`.

## After merge

1. Critic approves → **merge PR to `main` and `git push origin main`** (unless user forbade push).
2. **Documentation actualization** (same wave or immediate follow-up commit on `main`):
   - Master / phase plans → `done` + merge SHA
   - [README.md](../../README.md) — platform status, tests, deploy if user-facing
   - [CONTRIBUTING.md](../../CONTRIBUTING.md) — contributor test matrix
   - [.github/repo-description.txt](../../.github/repo-description.txt) + `make sync-github-metadata` when summary changes
   - Runtime / deploy docs per [veil-agent-documentation.mdc](veil-agent-documentation.mdc)
3. **Next phase** only from updated `main`, new branch.

## Git add (same as always)

```bash
git add -A -- . ':!data'
```

Never commit `data/`, secrets, or `**/__pycache__/`.
